mod.rs
     1Ôćĺ//! Structured logging.
     2Ôćĺ//!
     3Ôćĺ//! Add the `kv` feature to your `Cargo.toml` to enable
     4Ôćĺ//! this module:
     5Ôćĺ//!
     6Ôćĺ//! ```toml
     7Ôćĺ//! [dependencies.log]
     8Ôćĺ//! features = ["kv"]
     9Ôćĺ//! ```
    10Ôćĺ//!
    11Ôćĺ//! # Structured logging in `log`
    12Ôćĺ//!
    13Ôćĺ//! Structured logging enhances traditional text-based log records with user-defined
    14Ôćĺ//! attributes. Structured logs can be analyzed using a variety of data processing
    15Ôćĺ//! techniques, without needing to find and parse attributes from unstructured text first.
    16Ôćĺ//!
    17Ôćĺ//! In `log`, user-defined attributes are part of a [`Source`] on the log record.
    18Ôćĺ//! Each attribute is a key-value; a pair of [`Key`] and [`Value`]. Keys are strings
    19Ôćĺ//! and values are a datum of any type that can be formatted or serialized. Simple types
    20Ôćĺ//! like strings, booleans, and numbers are supported, as well as arbitrarily complex
    21Ôćĺ//! structures involving nested objects and sequences.
    22Ôćĺ//!
    23Ôćĺ//! ## Adding key-values to log records
    24Ôćĺ//!
    25Ôćĺ//! Key-values appear before the message format in the `log!` macros:
    26Ôćĺ//!
    27Ôćĺ//! ```
    28Ôćĺ//! # use log::info;
    29Ôćĺ//! info!(a = 1; "Something of interest");
    30Ôćĺ//! ```
    31Ôćĺ//!
    32Ôćĺ//! Key-values support the same shorthand identifier syntax as `format_args`:
    33Ôćĺ//!
    34Ôćĺ//! ```
    35Ôćĺ//! # use log::info;
    36Ôćĺ//! let a = 1;
    37Ôćĺ//!
    38Ôćĺ//! info!(a; "Something of interest");
    39Ôćĺ//! ```
      ÔćĺÔÇŽ
